{"title_page": "Donnie Tuck", "text_new": "{{Infobox Politician\n|birthname = Donnie Ray Tuck\n|image = \n|image_size = 220px\n|caption =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|08|16|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Chapel Hill]], [[North Carolina]], U.S.\n|office             = [[List of mayors of Hampton, Virginia|Mayor of Hampton, Virginia]]\n|term_start         = July 1, 2016\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = [[George E. Wallace]]\n|successor          = \n|party = [[Independent]]\n|religion = \n|alma_mater = [[Duke University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Old Dominion University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]])\n|spouse = Robie E. Tuck\n}}\n\n'''Donnie Ray Tuck''' (born August 16, 1954) is an American politician who is currently serving as mayor of [[Hampton, Virginia]]. He defeated incumbent mayor [[George E. Wallace]] in [[2016 Hampton, Virginia mayoral election|2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/hampton/dp-nws-hampton-mayor-voter-guide-20160501-story.html |title=Wallace seeks re-election, Tuck seeks change in Hampton mayor's race |publisher=Daily Press |date= |accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/hampton/dp-hampton-mayor-george-wallace-loses-race-to-donnie-tuck-20160503-story.html |title=Donnie Tuck unseats incumbent Hampton mayor George Wallace |publisher=Daily Press |date= |accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref> Tuck made his first bid for elected office in Hampton in 2003, to succeed [[Mary Christian (politician)|Mary Christian]] in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]]; he lost the Democratic primary to [[Jeion Ward]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of mayors of Hampton, Virginia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|before= [[George E. Wallace]]\n|title=[[List of mayors of Hampton, Virginia|Mayor of Hampton, Virginia]]\n|years= 2016\u2013present\n|after= Incumbent\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n}}\n{{Virginia cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Politics|Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuck, Donnie}}\n[[Category:Mayors of Hampton, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia Independents]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Old Dominion University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Virginia-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Politician\n|birthname = Donnie Ray Tuck\n|image = \n|image_size = 220px\n|caption =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|08|16|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Orange]], [[North Carolina]], U.S.\n|office             = [[List of mayors of Hampton, Virginia|Mayor of Hampton, Virginia]]\n|term_start         = July 1, 2016\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = [[George E. Wallace]]\n|successor          = \n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|religion = \n|alma_mater = [[Duke University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Old Dominion University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]])\n|spouse = Robie E. Retherford\n|signature = Donnie Tuck signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Donnie Ray Tuck''' (born August 16, 1954) is an American politician who is currently serving as mayor of [[Hampton, Virginia]]. He defeated incumbent mayor [[George E. Wallace]] in [[2016 Hampton, Virginia mayoral election|2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/hampton/dp-nws-hampton-mayor-voter-guide-20160501-story.html |title=Wallace seeks re-election, Tuck seeks change in Hampton mayor's race |publisher=Daily Press |date= |accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/hampton/dp-hampton-mayor-george-wallace-loses-race-to-donnie-tuck-20160503-story.html |title=Donnie Tuck unseats incumbent Hampton mayor George Wallace |publisher=Daily Press |date= |accessdate=2017-01-23}}</ref> Tuck made his first bid for elected office in 2003, to succeed [[Mary Christian (politician)|Mary Christian]] in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]]; he lost the Democratic primary to [[Jeion Ward]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of mayors of Hampton, Virginia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Offices and distinctions\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|before= [[George E. Wallace]]\n|title=[[List of mayors of Hampton, Virginia|Mayor of Hampton, Virginia]]\n|years= 2016\u2013present\n|after= Incumbent\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n}}\n{{Virginia cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Politics|Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuck, Donnie}}\n[[Category:Mayors of Hampton, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia Independents]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Old Dominion University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Virginia-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:8805:500:184a:e82c:1eb0:a8a5:e3d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Corrected statement about Political Party and removed signature.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donnie_Tuck"}
{"title_page": "Carl Niehaus", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n'''Carl Niehaus''' (born 25 December 1959)<ref name=\":0\" /> is the former spokesman for South African ruling party the [[African National Congress]], former spokesman for [[Nelson Mandela]], and was a political prisoner after being convicted of [[treason]] against South Africa. He stepped down as ANC spokesman in February 2009 after admitting to maladministration of his own finances, extensive borrowing from political contacts and fraud.  He is a vocal and noteworthy supporter of former President [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-04-06-ill-support-zuma-no-matter-what-says-carl-niehaus-outside-court/|title=I'll support Zuma no matter what\u201a says Carl Niehaus outside court|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Treason conviction and sentence==\nAs a young theology student,<ref name=\"#NYT1\">[[#NYT1|New York Times(1)]]</ref> Niehaus was reported to the [[security police]] by his flatmate, warrant officer Robert Whitecross, after confiding in him about blowing up the gasworks in [[Johannesburg]]. In 1983 he was convicted of treason and received a prison sentence of 15 years. <ref name=\"#News24(1)\">[[#News24(1)]]</ref> He was incarcerated on 25 November 1983 and released on 20 March 1991<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Niehaus|first=Carl|title=Om te veg vir hoop (to fight for hope)|publisher=Human & Rousseau|year=1993|isbn=0798132027|location=Cape Town, South Africa|pages=108, 131}}</ref>.<ref name=\"#NYT1\"/>\n\nIn 2008 he publicly disclosed that he was [[gang rape]]d in prison the night before his guilty verdict was handed down.<ref name=\"#IOL2\">[[#IOL2|Independent Online(2)]]</ref> The truth of this claim has subsequently been questioned by a former friend, Bart Luirink, editor of the Dutch ''Zuidelijk Afrika'' (''South Africa'') magazine<ref name=\"#IOL3\">[[#IOL3|Independent Online(3)]]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nIn February 2008 investigations by a number of media organisations found that Niehaus had falsely claimed to hold a master's degree and a doctorate in theology (''summa cum laude'') from the [[University of Utrecht]]. Claimed qualifications confirmed to be true included a Bachelor's in Theology from the [[University of South Africa]] (Unisa) awarded in April 1988 and an honours degree (''Cum Laude'') from the same institution two years later.<ref name=\"#News24(4)\">[[#News24(4)]]</ref><ref name=\"#Citizen(1)\">[[#Citizen(1)|The Citizen(1)]]</ref> \n\n==Career==\nIn 1994 he became the spokesman for Nelson Mandela and, subsequently, a member of parliament and the chairman of the correctional services committee.<ref name=\"#News24(1)\"/>\n\nIn late 1996 he was appointed South Africa's ambassador to the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"#Gov1\">[[#Gov1|South African government(1)]]</ref> At the end of his term as ambassador,<ref name=\"#News24(1)\"/> he became an executive director<ref name=\"#IOL1\">[[#IOL1|Independent Online(1)]]</ref> of [[Nicro]], the National Institute for Crime Prevention and the Reintegration of Offenders.\n\nIn late 2000<ref name=\"#News24(2)\">[[#News24(2)]]</ref> he became the joint chairman of the ''Home for all'' initiative, a campaign by white activists to apologise for apartheid.<ref name=\"#News24(1)\"/>\n\nIn 2020 Niehaus was subpoenaed to testify at the re-opened inquest into the death in detention of Neil Aggett after submitting an affidavit to the effect that he (Niehaus) was badly tortured at the hands of the security police when in detention. <ref>https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/carl-niehaus-to-be-subpoenaed-to-appear-at-inquiry-into-aggetts-death-42641260</ref>\n\n===2009 scandal===\nIn February 2009 Niehaus stepped down as spokesman for the ANC after a newspaper reported on a \"broad trail of bad debt and broken promises\" stemming from his personal financial mismanagement, including one instance of fraud, and claiming that his sister had died.<ref>https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-10-25-unforgiven-the-extraordinary-tale-of-carl-niehaus/#.Wx_DuKmLnVo</ref><ref>https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/niehaus-fraud-anc-knew-all-about-it-434520</ref> Niehaus confessed to most of the allegations against him in the same article.<ref name=\"#MG1\">[[#MG1|Mail & Guardian(1)]]</ref>\n\nParts of his confession were questioned on the same day, when the [[Gauteng]] provincial government said it had independently discovered that Niehaus had forged the signatures of provincial ministers to secure a loan. Niehaus claimed he had confessed the forgery within hours of committing it.<ref name=\"#Times1\">[[#Times1|The Times(1)]]</ref>\n\nNiehaus stepped down as spokesman of the ANC the same day in what the party described as a mutual decision.<ref name=\"#iAfrica1\">[[#iAfrica1|iAfrica.com(1)]]</ref>\n\nHis debts were later estimated to total nearly R4.5 million.<ref name=\"#Times2\">[[#Times2|The Times(2)]]</ref> It was reported in 2017 that Neihaus was still in debt and concocting what appeared to be a fraudulent scheme to get out of trouble.<ref>https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/2017-12-09-carl-of-the-dead-and-debt-cooks-up-scheme-to-avoid-r4m-bill-/</ref> <ref>https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2018-05-12-carl-niehaus-runs-short-of-cash-again-as-new-debt-woes-mount/</ref>\n\n=== 2017 ANC presidential campaign ===\nIn 2017 Niehaus reemerged as a spokesperson for the [[Umkhonto we Sizwe Military Veterans\u2019 Association]] and a key member of the campaign team for [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]'s failed bid for the ANC presidency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-10-25-unforgiven-the-extraordinary-tale-of-carl-niehaus|title=Unforgiven: The extraordinary tale of Carl Niehaus {{!}} Daily Maverick|website=www.dailymaverick.co.za|language=en|access-date=2017-10-26}}</ref> In mid 2018, the MKMVA apparently apologised to the ANC for statements made by Niehaus regarding the land question.<ref>https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1973037/mkmva-apologises-to-anc-for-carl-niehaus-apology-to-king/</ref> \n\nHe gained brief fame for his dancing during one campaign event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/news-eish/1719642/watch-how-social-media-unpacked-this-video-of-niehaus-and-van-rooyen-dancing/|title=WATCH: How social media unpacked this video of Niehaus and Van Rooyen dancing|last=reporter|first=Citizen|work=The Citizen|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/11/06/carl-niehaus-dancing-behind-zuma-is-what-the-doctor-ordered_a_23267806/|title=Carl Niehaus Dancing Behind Zuma Is What The Doctor Ordered|date=2017-11-06|work=Huffington Post South Africa|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en-ZA}}</ref>\n\nLate in 2017, Niehaus stated that he would be complaining to Wikipedia about being called a \"massive [[poes]] and an embarrassment to the human race\".<ref>https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/carl-niehaus-wikipedia-page-edited-to-call-him-an-embarrassment-to-the-human-race-20171213</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n=== 2020 Stalking Allegations ===\n\n\nIn February 2020 Niehaus found himself at the receiving end of insults and ridicule after claiming he was stalked and being followed by Chris Vick, who in turn called Niehaus a \u201cparanoid idiot\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/social-media/2246750/paranoid-idiot-carl-niehaus-slammed-for-asking-mk-vets-to-protect-him/|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1986 Niehaus married Jansie Lourens, who had recruited him into the armed struggle against apartheid and who was sentenced to four years for the same treason plot that saw Niehaus jailed.<ref name=\":0\" /> The couple divorced in 2002 and Niehaus married Linda Thango.<ref name=\"#News24(3)\">[[#News24(3)]]</ref>\n\nIn September 2008 he married businesswoman Mafani Gunguluza<ref name=\"#IOL3\"/>, and in 2012 he told 702 Radio that they had separated.<ref>https://mg.co.za/article/2012-05-04-three-weddings-and-a-funeral</ref> In 2019 he was reported as having a new girlfriend. <ref>https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/social-media/2188274/carl-niehaus-defends-23-year-old-girlfriend-against-internet-trolls/</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n\n*{{cite news\n|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE0D8113EF932A25753C1A964958260\n|title=Apartheid's Children: Afrikaner Writers Today\n|publisher=New York Times\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n| first=Christopher S.\n| last=Wren\n| date=11 October 1992\n|ref=NYT1}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2469491,00.html \n |title=Tearful Carl confesses all \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=News24(1) \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215073322/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0%2C%2C2-7-12_2469491%2C00.html \n |archivedate=15 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,9294,2-7-12_987997,00.html\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070720205449/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,9294,2-7-12_987997,00.html\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2007-07-20\n |title=''Home for All'' endorsed by 900 \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=News24(2) \n}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/0,9294,2-7_1165442,00.html \n |title=Carl Niehaus divorcing Jansie \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=News24(3) \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216122022/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/0%2C9294%2C2-7_1165442%2C00.html \n |archivedate=16 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2472072,00.html \n |title=Fact check: Carl Niehaus \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-20 \n |ref=News24(4) \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223093550/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0%2C%2C2-7-12_2472072%2C00.html \n |archivedate=23 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite news\n|url=http://www.time.com/time/europe/magazine/2001/0108/apology.html\n|title=The Trouble with \"Sorry\"\n|publisher=Time magazine\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n| date=8 January 2001\n|ref=Time(1)}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.search.gov.za/info/previewDocument.jsp?dk=%2Fdata%2Fstatic%2Finfo%2Fspeeches%2F1996%2F12300w50496.htm%40Gov&q=(+(dc.Date%3E%3D1996%2F01%2F01)%3CAND%3E(dc.Date%3C%3D1996%2F12%2F31)+)%3CAND%3E(category%3Ccontains%3Es)&t=NEW+SA+HEADS+OF+DIPLOMATIC+MISSIONS \n |title=Appointment of new South African heads of diplomatic missions, 23 December 1996 \n |publisher=South African government \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=Gov1 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728191120/http://www.search.gov.za/info/previewDocument.jsp?dk=%2Fdata%2Fstatic%2Finfo%2Fspeeches%2F1996%2F12300w50496.htm%40Gov&q=%28+%28dc.Date%3E%3D1996%2F01%2F01%29%3CAND%3E%28dc.Date%3C%3D1996%2F12%2F31%29+%29%3CAND%3E%28category%3Ccontains%3Es%29&t=NEW+SA+HEADS+OF+DIPLOMATIC+MISSIONS \n |archivedate=28 July 2011 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct2000090609250695C656578\n|title=Taxpayers face R6bn prisons bill\n|publisher=Independent Online\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=IOL1}}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=6&art_id=vn20080616070006829C359475\n|title=Niehaus tells of prison horror\n|publisher=Independent Online\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=IOL2}}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=vn20090220053953591C667704\n|title=Niehaus's lobola splurge\n|publisher=Independent Online\n|accessdate=2009-02-20\n|ref=IOL3}}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2009-02-13-tearful-niehaus-admits-fraud\n|title=Tearful Niehaus admits fraud\n|publisher=Mail & Guardian\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=MG1}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=939043 \n |title=Gauteng denies Niehaus claims \n |publisher=The Times \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=Times1 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214163542/http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=939043 \n |archivedate=14 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=942452 \n |title=Niehaus owes R4.5m \n |publisher=The Times \n |accessdate=2009-02-20 \n |ref=Times2 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222212355/http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=942452 \n |archivedate=22 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://news.iafrica.com/sa/1294784.htm\n|title=Niehaus steps down\n|publisher=iAfrica.com\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=iAfrica1\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218130059/http://news.iafrica.com/sa/1294784.htm\n|archive-date=18 February 2009\n|url-status=dead\n}}\n\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.citizen.co.za/index/article.aspx?pDesc=89625,1,22\n |title=Niehaus's degree claims proved to be false \n |publisher=The Citizen \n |accessdate=2009-02-20 \n |ref=Citizen(1) \n}}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090527024705/http://www.uu.nl/NL/onderzoek/toponderzoekers/internationalemedailles/Pages/default.aspx Website Universiteit van Utrecht, accessdate 2009-03-16]\n\n{{Authority control}}{{Jacob Zuma}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Niehaus, Carl}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of South Africa to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:South African prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of South Africa]]\n[[Category:People convicted of treason]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n'''Carl Niehaus''' (born 25 December 1959)<ref name=\":0\" /> is the former spokesman for South African ruling party the [[African National Congress]], former spokesman for [[Nelson Mandela]], and was a political prisoner after being convicted of [[treason]] against South Africa. He stepped down as ANC spokesman in February 2009 after admitting to maladministration of his own finances, extensive borrowing from political contacts and fraud.  He is a vocal and noteworthy supporter of former President [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-04-06-ill-support-zuma-no-matter-what-says-carl-niehaus-outside-court/|title=I'll support Zuma no matter what\u201a says Carl Niehaus outside court|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Treason conviction and sentence==\nAs a young theology student,<ref name=\"#NYT1\">[[#NYT1|New York Times(1)]]</ref> Niehaus was reported to the [[security police]] by his flatmate, warrant officer Robert Whitecross, after confiding in him about blowing up the gasworks in [[Johannesburg]]. In 1983 he was convicted of treason and received a prison sentence of 15 years. <ref name=\"#News24(1)\">[[#News24(1)]]</ref> He was incarcerated on 25 November 1983 and released on 20 March 1991<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Niehaus|first=Carl|title=Om te veg vir hoop (to fight for hope)|publisher=Human & Rousseau|year=1993|isbn=0798132027|location=Cape Town, South Africa|pages=108, 131}}</ref>.<ref name=\"#NYT1\"/>\n\nIn 2008 he publicly disclosed that he was [[gang rape]]d in prison the night before his guilty verdict was handed down.<ref name=\"#IOL2\">[[#IOL2|Independent Online(2)]]</ref> The truth of this claim has subsequently been questioned by a former friend, Bart Luirink, editor of the Dutch ''Zuidelijk Afrika'' (''South Africa'') magazine<ref name=\"#IOL3\">[[#IOL3|Independent Online(3)]]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nIn February 2008 investigations by a number of media organisations found that Niehaus had falsely claimed to hold a master's degree and a doctorate in theology (''summa cum laude'') from the [[University of Utrecht]]. Claimed qualifications confirmed to be true included a Bachelor's in Theology from the [[University of South Africa]] (Unisa) awarded in April 1988 and an honours degree (''Cum Laude'') from the same institution two years later.<ref name=\"#News24(4)\">[[#News24(4)]]</ref><ref name=\"#Citizen(1)\">[[#Citizen(1)|The Citizen(1)]]</ref> \n\n==Career==\nIn 1994 he became the spokesman for Nelson Mandela and, subsequently, a member of parliament and the chairman of the correctional services committee.<ref name=\"#News24(1)\"/>\n\nIn late 1996 he was appointed South Africa's ambassador to the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"#Gov1\">[[#Gov1|South African government(1)]]</ref> At the end of his term as ambassador,<ref name=\"#News24(1)\"/> he became an executive director<ref name=\"#IOL1\">[[#IOL1|Independent Online(1)]]</ref> of [[Nicro]], the National Institute for Crime Prevention and the Reintegration of Offenders.\n\nIn late 2000<ref name=\"#News24(2)\">[[#News24(2)]]</ref> he became the joint chairman of the ''Home for all'' initiative, a campaign by white activists to apologise for apartheid.<ref name=\"#News24(1)\"/>\n\nIn 2020 Niehaus was subpoenaed to testify at the re-opened inquest into the death in detention of Neil Aggett after submitting an affidavit to the effect that he (Niehaus) was badly tortured at the hands of the security police when in detention. <ref>https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/carl-niehaus-to-be-subpoenaed-to-appear-at-inquiry-into-aggetts-death-42641260</ref>\n\n===2009 scandal===\nIn February 2009 Niehaus stepped down as spokesman for the ANC after a newspaper reported on a \"broad trail of bad debt and broken promises\" stemming from his personal financial mismanagement, including one instance of fraud, and claiming that his sister had died.<ref>https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-10-25-unforgiven-the-extraordinary-tale-of-carl-niehaus/#.Wx_DuKmLnVo</ref><ref>https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/niehaus-fraud-anc-knew-all-about-it-434520</ref> Niehaus confessed to most of the allegations against him in the same article.<ref name=\"#MG1\">[[#MG1|Mail & Guardian(1)]]</ref>\n\nParts of his confession were questioned on the same day, when the [[Gauteng]] provincial government said it had independently discovered that Niehaus had forged the signatures of provincial ministers to secure a loan. Niehaus claimed he had confessed the forgery within hours of committing it.<ref name=\"#Times1\">[[#Times1|The Times(1)]]</ref>\n\nNiehaus stepped down as spokesman of the ANC the same day in what the party described as a mutual decision.<ref name=\"#iAfrica1\">[[#iAfrica1|iAfrica.com(1)]]</ref>\n\nHis debts were later estimated to total nearly R4.5 million.<ref name=\"#Times2\">[[#Times2|The Times(2)]]</ref> It was reported in 2017 that Neihaus was still in debt and concocting what appeared to be a fraudulent scheme to get out of trouble.<ref>https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/2017-12-09-carl-of-the-dead-and-debt-cooks-up-scheme-to-avoid-r4m-bill-/</ref> <ref>https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2018-05-12-carl-niehaus-runs-short-of-cash-again-as-new-debt-woes-mount/</ref>\n\n=== 2017 ANC presidential campaign ===\nIn 2017 Niehaus reemerged as a spokesperson for the [[Umkhonto we Sizwe Military Veterans\u2019 Association]] and a key member of the campaign team for [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]'s failed bid for the ANC presidency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-10-25-unforgiven-the-extraordinary-tale-of-carl-niehaus|title=Unforgiven: The extraordinary tale of Carl Niehaus {{!}} Daily Maverick|website=www.dailymaverick.co.za|language=en|access-date=2017-10-26}}</ref> In mid 2018, the MKMVA apparently apologised to the ANC for statements made by Niehaus regarding the land question.<ref>https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/1973037/mkmva-apologises-to-anc-for-carl-niehaus-apology-to-king/</ref> \n\nHe gained brief fame for his dancing during one campaign event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/news-eish/1719642/watch-how-social-media-unpacked-this-video-of-niehaus-and-van-rooyen-dancing/|title=WATCH: How social media unpacked this video of Niehaus and Van Rooyen dancing|last=reporter|first=Citizen|work=The Citizen|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/11/06/carl-niehaus-dancing-behind-zuma-is-what-the-doctor-ordered_a_23267806/|title=Carl Niehaus Dancing Behind Zuma Is What The Doctor Ordered|date=2017-11-06|work=Huffington Post South Africa|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en-ZA}}</ref>\n\nLate in 2017, Niehaus stated that he would be complaining to Wikipedia about being called a \"massive [[poes]] and an embarrassment to the human race\".<ref>https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/carl-niehaus-wikipedia-page-edited-to-call-him-an-embarrassment-to-the-human-race-20171213</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n=== 2020 Stalking Allegations ===\n\n\nIn February 2020 Niehaus found himself at the receiving end of insults and ridicule after claiming he was stalked and being followed by Chris Vick, who in turn called Niehaus a \u201cparanoid idiot\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/social-media/2246750/paranoid-idiot-carl-niehaus-slammed-for-asking-mk-vets-to-protect-him/|website=citizen.co.za|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1986 Niehaus married Jansie Lourens, who had recruited him into the armed struggle against apartheid and who was sentenced to four years for the same treason plot that saw Niehaus jailed. The couple divorced in 2002 and Niehaus married Linda Thango.<ref name=\"#News24(3)\">[[#News24(3)]]</ref>\n\nIn September 2008 he married businesswoman Mafani Gunguluza<ref name=\"#IOL3\"/>, and in 2012 he told 702 Radio that they had separated.<ref>https://mg.co.za/article/2012-05-04-three-weddings-and-a-funeral</ref> In 2019 he was reported as having a new girlfriend. <ref>https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/social-media/2188274/carl-niehaus-defends-23-year-old-girlfriend-against-internet-trolls/</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n\n*{{cite news\n|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE0D8113EF932A25753C1A964958260\n|title=Apartheid's Children: Afrikaner Writers Today\n|publisher=New York Times\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n| first=Christopher S.\n| last=Wren\n| date=11 October 1992\n|ref=NYT1}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_2469491,00.html \n |title=Tearful Carl confesses all \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=News24(1) \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215073322/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0%2C%2C2-7-12_2469491%2C00.html \n |archivedate=15 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,9294,2-7-12_987997,00.html\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070720205449/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,9294,2-7-12_987997,00.html\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2007-07-20\n |title=''Home for All'' endorsed by 900 \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=News24(2) \n}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/0,9294,2-7_1165442,00.html \n |title=Carl Niehaus divorcing Jansie \n |publisher=News24 \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=News