6829C359475\n|title=Niehaus tells of prison horror\n|publisher=Independent Online\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=IOL2}}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=vn20090220053953591C667704\n|title=Niehaus's lobola splurge\n|publisher=Independent Online\n|accessdate=2009-02-20\n|ref=IOL3}}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2009-02-13-tearful-niehaus-admits-fraud\n|title=Tearful Niehaus admits fraud\n|publisher=Mail & Guardian\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=MG1}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=939043 \n |title=Gauteng denies Niehaus claims \n |publisher=The Times \n |accessdate=2009-02-13 \n |ref=Times1 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214163542/http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=939043 \n |archivedate=14 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web \n |url=http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=942452 \n |title=Niehaus owes R4.5m \n |publisher=The Times \n |accessdate=2009-02-20 \n |ref=Times2 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222212355/http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=942452 \n |archivedate=22 February 2009 \n |df=dmy \n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://news.iafrica.com/sa/1294784.htm\n|title=Niehaus steps down\n|publisher=iAfrica.com\n|accessdate=2009-02-13\n|ref=iAfrica1\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090218130059/http://news.iafrica.com/sa/1294784.htm\n|archive-date=18 February 2009\n|url-status=dead\n}}\n\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.citizen.co.za/index/article.aspx?pDesc=89625,1,22\n |title=Niehaus's degree claims proved to be false \n |publisher=The Citizen \n |accessdate=2009-02-20 \n |ref=Citizen(1) \n}}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090527024705/http://www.uu.nl/NL/onderzoek/toponderzoekers/internationalemedailles/Pages/default.aspx Website Universiteit van Utrecht, accessdate 2009-03-16]\n\n{{Authority control}}{{Jacob Zuma}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Niehaus, Carl}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of South Africa to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:South African prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of South Africa]]\n[[Category:People convicted of treason]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "J0hnst5v5ns", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citation added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Niehaus"}
{"title_page": "William Hoskins (inventor)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image         = Chemist William Hoskins and family ca 1885.png<!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = William Hoskins, with daughter Florence and wife Ada, ''ca.'' 1885\u20131890\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 1862\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1934 (aged 72)\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Inventor\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = Billiard chalk, electric heating coil\n}}\n'''William Hoskins''' (1862\u20131934)<ref name=\"CHiC1\">[http://chemhistory-chicago.org/1843.html \"C.H.i.C. Timeline 1843\u20131880\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813122642/http://chemhistory-chicago.org/1843.html |date=August 13, 2011 }}, ''A Guide to the Chemical History of Chicago'', Chemical History in Chicago Project, date unspecified; accessed February 24, 2007</ref><ref name=\"CHiC2\">[http://chemhistory-chicago.org/details.php?pid=124 \"CHiC Details: Hoskins, William\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006220903/http://chemhistory-chicago.org/details.php?pid=124 |date=October 6, 2007 }}, ''A Guide to the Chemical History of Chicago'', Chemical History in Chicago Project, date unspecified; accessed February 24, 2007</ref><ref name=\"BookChic\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xlQDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA343&dq=%22Hoskins,+William%22+Chicagoans#PPA344,M1 |title=The Book of Chicagoans: A Biographical Dictionary of Leading Living Men of the City of Chicago |volume=Vol. 2 |section=\"William Hoskins\" entry |page=343 |last1=Leonard |first1=John William |last2=Marquis |first2=Albert Nelson |publisher=self-published |date=1911}} The entry can also be found on [https://books.google.com/books?id=OyV4vWP7aG4C&pg=PA296&dq=%22William+Hoskins%22+Chicagoans&lr=#PPA297,M1 p. 296 of the orig. 1905 ed.] Subsequent editions (1917, 1926) were titled ''Who's Who in Chicago''.</ref> was an [[United States|American]] inventor, chemist, electrical engineer, and entrepreneur in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, most active in [[Chicago, Illinois]].  He became the co-inventor in 1897 of modern {{Cuegloss|Chalk|billiard chalk}} with professional [[carom billiards]] player [[William A. Spinks]].<ref name=\"Clark1\">[http://www.toaster.org/hoskins_tragic.html \"The World's Most Tragic Man Is the One Who Never Starts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825063214/http://www.toaster.org/hoskins_tragic.html |date=August 25, 2006 }}, Clark, Neil M.; originally published in ''The American'' magazine, May 1927; republished in ''Hotwire: The Newsletter of the Toaster Museum Foundation'', vol. 3, no. 3, online edition; accessed February 24, 2007.  The piece is largely an interview of Hoskins.</ref><ref name=\"Patent578514\">{{US patent|0578514}}, March 9, 1897</ref> He is, however, best known for the invention of the electric heating coil \u2013 the basis for numerous ubiquitous household and industrial appliances, including electric stoves, space heaters, and toasters \u2013 and the invention of the first electric toaster.<ref name=\"beth_Page\">{{Cite web |title=Toasters {} BETHANY MISSION GALLERY |work=BETHANY MISSION GALLERY |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url=http://bethanymissiongallery.org/toasters.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331222130/http://www.bethanymissiongallery.org/toasters.html |archive-date=March 31, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"wayw_Hosk\">{{Cite web |title=Hoskins Manufacturing Company {{!}} People {{!}} The Collection of Historical Scientific Instruments |author= |work=waywiser.fas.harvard.edu |date= |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url= http://waywiser.fas.harvard.edu/people/1644/hoskins-manufacturing-company;jsessionid=0F846DE7862BAF216FCFE9B0675494EE |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early life===\nWilliam Hoskins was born in 1862 to parents John and Mary Ann Hoskins, in [[Chicago]].<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Hoskins would complete just two of three years of [[Chicago High School]];<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> despite having an interest in chemistry, he would gain no formal education in chemistry throughout his early years.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> Hoskins, however, received \"private instruction\" in the field,<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> before joining (at age thirteen), the Illinois State Microscopical Society. Four years later, at 17, the society elected him secretary.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" />\n\nAfter leaving high school in 1880 at age 17, Hoskins prepared chemical analysis samples<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> for Chicago-based consulting and analytical chemist Guy A. Mariner in the latter's commercial laboratory,<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /> starting in February.<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Beginning in 1880, Mariner was one of only three completely commercial chemists in Chicago.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> Five years after joining the laboratory, Hoskins became Mariner's partner; the firm was renamed ''Mariner and Hoskins''.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Shortly before becoming the partner, Hoskins married Mariner's daughter,<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> Ada Mae,{{efn|Both Mae<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /> and May<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> have been used}} in December 18, 1883.<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> In 1890, Hoskins became sole proprietor of the laboratory.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> The couple subsequently had four children: Minna, Edward, William and Florence.<ref name=\"BookChic\" />\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1897, Hoskins began working with [[William A. Spinks]] before becoming a partner in William A. Spinks & Co.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> In the early 1900s, Hoskins would also become the director of '''Hoskins Manufacturing Co.''', based in Detroit, creating electric heating appliances and pyrometers.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> He was made a [[fellow]] of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS),<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> and was also a charter member of the Chicago section of the [[American Chemical Society]] (ACS),<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"CHiC3\">{{Cite web |url=http://chemhistory-chicago.org/acs.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 25, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516103138/http://chemhistory-chicago.org/acs.html |archive-date=May 16, 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref> of which he was the chairman in 1897,<ref name=\"CHiC3\" /> later becoming the national ACS's vice-president,.<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Hoskins Manufacturing eventually become '''Hoskins Process Development Co.''', of which he was the president.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" />    Hoskins became a recognized scientific expert witness in lawsuits,<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> took out 37 US patents,<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> and in Hoskins's lab, [[Albert L. Marsh]] developed [[nichrome]] under supervision of Hoskins.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"hotw_Cutt\">{{Cite web |title=Cutting wire choice for foam cutters and CNC cutting machines - |work=Hotwire Systems |access-date=January 2, 2019 |url=https://hotwiresystems.com/nichrome-cutting-wire-for-foam-cutters-and-cnc-machines/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215063511/http://www.hotwiresystems.com/nichrome-cutting-wire-for-foam-cutters-and-cnc-machines/ |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Hoskins's own innovations include a superior billiard chalk, materials used to construct race tracks (including the Washington Park Race Tracks in Chicago), safety paper for bank checks, a method for destroying weeds, and a gasoline blowtorch.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"magazineclipping\"/>\n\n==Inventions==\n===Electric heating coil===\nWilliam Hoskins is credited with invention of the electric [[Heating element|heating coil]]. In the early 1900s, having worked on a form of [[nichrome]] known as [[chromel]], working with Marsh over the alloy he deduced the usage which could be used as a heating element.<ref name=\"magazineclipping\">{{Cite web |title=The William Hoskins I know |author=Redman, L.V. |work=repository.library.northwestern.edu |date= |access-date=January 2, 2019 |url= http://repository.library.northwestern.edu/fedora/get/inu:inu-mntb-0005391474-pg-7e363cb4-0029-4057-b60e-342a6e4704f0/PDF|publisher=The Chemical Bulletin |language= |quote=}}</ref> The heating coil was created using nichrome, and was later used in early versions of [[Toaster#Development of the heating element|the toaster]], and the [[Kettle#Electric kettles|electric kettle]].<ref name=\"George 2003\">{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SzdrtFSFG6IC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=%22William+Hoskins%22+high-resistance+wire+electric+heating | title=Antique Electric Waffle Irons 1900\u20131960: A History of the Appliance Industry in 20th Century America | last=George | first=William F. | publisher=Trafford Publishing | year=2003 | page=20 | accessdate=August 16, 2008 | isbn=1-55395-632-X }}</ref> The heating coil was one of the first projects for ''Hoskins Manufacturing Co.''; Hoskins had considered manufacturing toasters, but later abandoned the plans to focus on the coil itself.<ref name=\"esl-_Adva\">{{Cite web |title=Advanced Level: Reading Comprehension - Sentence Gap Fill - History of the Toaster - Answer Sheet {{!}} ESL Lounge |work=ESL Lounge |access-date=January 2, 2019 |url=http://www.esl-lounge.com/level5/level-5-advanced-reading-toasters-sentence-gap-fill-ans.php |quote=AEH's proximity to Hoskins Manufacturing and the fact that the patent was filed only two months after the Marsh patents suggests collaboration and that the device was to use chromel wiring. One of the first applications the Hoskins company had considered for chromel was toasters, but eventually abandoned such efforts to focus on making the wire itself. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831155343/http://www.esl-lounge.com/level5/level-5-advanced-reading-toasters-sentence-gap-fill-ans.php |archive-date=August 31, 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Billiard chalk===\n[[Image:Spinks Billiard Chalk box top ca 1900.jpg|thumb|right|Box top of a box of a dozen cubes of William A. Spinks Company billiard chalk, ca. 1900\u20131910. Note the endorsement by champion [[Jacob Schaefer Sr.]]]]\n\nIn the late 19th century,<ref name=\"jdmi_andW\">{{Cite web |title=William Hoskins for cue chalk  |author= |work=Days to Remember |date= |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url= https://jdmitchelldesigns.wordpress.com/tag/and-william-hoskins-for-cue-chalk/ }}</ref> actual [[chalk]] (generally [[calcium]] [[carbonate]], also known as [[calcite]] or carbonate of [[Calcium oxide|lime]]) was often used in [[cue sport]]s on the leather tips of [[cue stick]]s to better grip the [[Billiard ball|cue ball]], but players experimented with other powdery, abrasive substances, since chalk itself was {{em|too}} abrasive, and over time damaged the game equipment.<ref name=\"Tobey1\">Tobey, Eddie (November 9, 2006). \"Billiards Chalk\", ''EZineArticles.com''; retrieved February 24, 2007. Blocked URL: ezinearticles.com/?Billiards-Chalk&id=354398 {{Unreliable source?|date=January 2010|reason=eZineArticle is like AllExperts.com and WP itself, a tertiary source that we can't use.}}</ref><ref name=\"Russell1\">[http://ezinearticles.com/?Billiards---The-Transformation-Years-1845---1897&id=117753 \"Billiards \u2014 The Transformation Years: 1845\u20131897\"], Russell, Michael; ''EZineArticles.com'', December 23, 2005; retrieved 24 February 24, 2007. The article was used as the source for ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'', season 6, episode [http://www.crimelab.nl/transcripts.php?series=1&season=6&episode=22 \"Time of Your Death\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213083800/http://www.crimelab.nl/transcripts.php?series=1&season=6&episode=22 |date=February 13, 2012 }}, in which pool chalk plays a small but crucial role; the show perpetuated the \"axolite\" for \"aloxite\" error in this article.</ref> In 1892,<ref name=\"Russell1\" /> the aforementioned [[Balkline and straight rail|straight rail billiards]] pro William Spinks was particularly impressed by a piece of natural chalk-like substance obtained in [[France]], and presented it to Hoskins for analysis.  Hoskins, having encountered such material before, was able to determine that it was [[Volcanism|volcanic]] ash ([[pumice]]), probably from [[Mount Etna]], [[Sicily]].  The two of them experimented with different formulations to achieve the cue ball \"{{Cuegloss|Action|action}}\" that Spinks sought.<ref name=\"Clark1\" />\n\nThey settled on a mixture of Illinois-sourced<ref name=\"Clark1\" /> [[silica]] with small amounts of [[corundum]] or aloxite<ref name=\"Patent578514\" /> ([[aluminum]] [[oxide]], AL<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>),<ref name=\"Chem1\">[http://www.chemindustry.com/chemicals/14835.html \"Aloxite\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070625100844/http://www.chemindustry.com/chemicals/14835.html |date=June 25, 2007 }}, ''ChemIndustry.com'' database, retrieved February 24, 2007.</ref><ref name=\"PubChem\">[https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?sid=158,243 \"Substance Summary: Aluminum Oxide\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406175207/http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?sid=158,243 |date=April 6, 2014 }}, ''PubChem Database'', National Library of Medicine, US National Institutes of Health, retrieved February 24, 2007.</ref> founding the William A. Spinks Company in Chicago<ref name=\"Clark1\" /> after securing a patent on March 9, 1897.<ref name=\"Patent578514\" />  Spinks later left the company, but it retained his name and was subsequently run by Hoskins, and later by Hoskins's cousin<ref name=\"Clark1\" /> Edmund F. {{sic|hide=y|Hoskin|reason=His side of the family dropped the -s at the end of the surname.}},<ref name=\"Patent1524132\">{{US patent|1524132}}, January 27, 1925.</ref> after Hoskins moved on to other projects.\n\nThe William A. Spinks Company product (still emulated by modern manufacturers with slightly different, proprietary silicate compounds) effectively revolutionized billiards,<ref name=\"Tobey1\" /><ref name=\"Russell1\" /> by providing a cue tip friction enhancer that allowed the tip to grip the cue ball briefly<ref name=\"Patent578514\" /> and impart a previously unattainable amount of {{sic|hide=y|reason=Not capitalized in this context.|\"{{Cuegloss|english}}\"}} (spin),<ref name=\"Russell1\" /> which consequently allowed more precise and more extreme {{Cuegloss|Position|cue ball control}}, made {{Cuegloss|Miscue|miscuing}} less likely, made {{Cuegloss|Semi-mass\u00e9|swerve}} and {{lang|fr|{{Cuegloss|mass\u00e9}}}} (curve, or even reversing) shots plausible, and eventually spawned the cue sport of [[artistic billiards]] almost a century later.  Even the basic {{Cuegloss|draw}} and {{Cuegloss|follow}} shots of modern billiards games depend heavily on the effects and properties of modern billiard \"chalk\".<ref name=\"bill_Pool\">{{Cite web |title=Pool Pointers: pool\\billiard instruction featuring photos of famous pool players by Billie Billing and Billie Billiard Promotions |work=billiebilliards.com |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url= https://www.billiebilliards.com/pointers006.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131227020451/http://www.billiebilliards.com/pointers006.html |archive-date=December 27, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n<!--\nONES TO WORK INTO THIS:\n*\"Chairmen of the Chicago Section of ACS\", A Guide to the Chemical History of Chicago. [http://chemhistory-chicago.org/acs.htm]\n*http://www.toaster.org/hoskins.html\n*http://www.toaster.org/hoskins2.html\n*http://www.toaster.org/toastove.html -->\n\n{{Cue sports nav}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoskins, William}}\n[[Category:American carom billiards players]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image         = Chemist William Hoskins and family ca 1885.png<!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = William Hoskins, with daughter Florence and wife Ada, ''ca.'' 1885\u20131890\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 1862\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1934 (aged 72)\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Inventor\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = Billiard chalk, electric heating coil\n}}\n'''William Hoskins''' (1862\u20131934)<ref name=\"CHiC1\">[http://chemhistory-chicago.org/1843.html \"C.H.i.C. Timeline 1843\u20131880\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813122642/http://chemhistory-chicago.org/1843.html |date=August 13, 2011 }}, ''A Guide to the Chemical History of Chicago'', Chemical History in Chicago Project, date unspecified; accessed February 24, 2007</ref><ref name=\"CHiC2\">[http://chemhistory-chicago.org/details.php?pid=124 \"CHiC Details: Hoskins, William\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006220903/http://chemhistory-chicago.org/details.php?pid=124 |date=October 6, 2007 }}, ''A Guide to the Chemical History of Chicago'', Chemical History in Chicago Project, date unspecified; accessed February 24, 2007</ref><ref name=\"BookChic\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xlQDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA343&dq=%22Hoskins,+William%22+Chicagoans#PPA344,M1 |title=The Book of Chicagoans: A Biographical Dictionary of Leading Living Men of the City of Chicago |volume=Vol. 2 |section=\"William Hoskins\" entry |page=343 |last1=Leonard |first1=John William |last2=Marquis |first2=Albert Nelson |publisher=self-published |date=1911}} The entry can also be found on [https://books.google.com/books?id=OyV4vWP7aG4C&pg=PA296&dq=%22William+Hoskins%22+Chicagoans&lr=#PPA297,M1 p. 296 of the orig. 1905 ed.] Subsequent editions (1917, 1926) were titled ''Who's Who in Chicago''.</ref> was an [[United States|American]] inventor, chemist, electrical engineer, and entrepreneur in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, most active in [[Chicago, Illinois]].  He became the co-inventor in 1897 of modern {{Cuegloss|Chalk|billiard chalk}} with professional [[carom billiards]] player [[William A. Spinks]].<ref name=\"Clark1\">[http://www.toaster.org/hoskins_tragic.html \"The World's Most Tragic Man Is the One Who Never Starts\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825063214/http://www.toaster.org/hoskins_tragic.html |date=August 25, 2006 }}, Clark, Neil M.; originally published in ''The American'' magazine, May 1927; republished in ''Hotwire: The Newsletter of the Toaster Museum Foundation'', vol. 3, no. 3, online edition; accessed February 24, 2007.  The piece is largely an interview of Hoskins.</ref><ref name=\"Patent578514\">{{US patent|0578514}}, March 9, 1897</ref> He is, however, best known for the invention of the electric heating coil \u2013 the basis for numerous ubiquitous household and industrial appliances, including electric stoves, space heaters, and toasters \u2013 and the invention of the first electric toaster.<ref name=\"beth_Page\">{{Cite web |title=Toasters {} BETHANY MISSION GALLERY |work=BETHANY MISSION GALLERY |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url=http://bethanymissiongallery.org/toasters.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180331222130/http://www.bethanymissiongallery.org/toasters.html |archive-date=March 31, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"wayw_Hosk\">{{Cite web |title=Hoskins Manufacturing Company {{!}} People {{!}} The Collection of Historical Scientific Instruments |author= |work=waywiser.fas.harvard.edu |date= |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url= http://waywiser.fas.harvard.edu/people/1644/hoskins-manufacturing-company;jsessionid=0F846DE7862BAF216FCFE9B0675494EE |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early life===\nWilliam Hoskins was born in 1862 to parents John and Mary Ann Hoskins, in [[Chicago]].<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Hoskins would complete just two of three years of [[Chicago High School]];<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> despite having an interest in chemistry, he would gain no formal education in chemistry throughout his early years.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> Hoskins, however, received \"private instruction\" in the field,<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> before joining (at age thirteen), the Illinois State Microscopical Society. Four years later, at 17, the society elected him secretary.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" />\n\nAfter leaving high school in 1880 at age 17, Hoskins prepared chemical analysis samples<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> for Chicago-based consulting and analytical chemist Guy A. Mariner in the latter's commercial laboratory,<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /> starting in February.<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Beginning in 1880, Mariner was one of only three completely commercial chemists in Chicago.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> Five years after joining the laboratory, Hoskins became Mariner's partner; the firm was renamed ''Mariner and Hoskins''.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Shortly before becoming the partner, Hoskins married Mariner's daughter,<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> Ada Mae,{{efn|Both Mae<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /> and May<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> have been used}} in December 18, 1883.<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> In 1890, Hoskins became sole proprietor of the laboratory.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> The couple subsequently had four children: Minna, Edward, William and Florence.<ref name=\"BookChic\" />\n\n===Later career===\nIn 1897, Hoskins began working with [[William A. Spinks]] before becoming a partner in William A. Spinks & Co.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> In the early 1900s, Hoskins would also become the director of '''Hoskins Manufacturing Co.''', based in Detroit, creating electric heating appliances and pyrometers.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"BookChic\" /> He was made a [[fellow]] of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS),<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> and was also a charter member of the Chicago section of the [[American Chemical Society]] (ACS),<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"CHiC3\">{{Cite web |url=http://chemhistory-chicago.org/acs.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 25, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516103138/http://chemhistory-chicago.org/acs.html |archive-date=May 16, 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref> of which he was the chairman in 1897,<ref name=\"CHiC3\" /> later becoming the national ACS's vice-president,.<ref name=\"BookChic\" /> Hoskins Manufacturing eventually become '''Hoskins Process Development Co.''', of which he was the president.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" />    Hoskins became a recognized scientific expert witness in lawsuits,<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> took out 37 US patents,<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /> and in Hoskins's lab, [[Albert L. Marsh]] developed [[nichrome]] under supervision of Hoskins.<ref name=\"CHiC1\" /><ref name=\"hotw_Cutt\">{{Cite web |title=Cutting wire choice for foam cutters and CNC cutting machines - |work=Hotwire Systems |access-date=January 2, 2019 |url=https://hotwiresystems.com/nichrome-cutting-wire-for-foam-cutters-and-cnc-machines/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215063511/http://www.hotwiresystems.com/nichrome-cutting-wire-for-foam-cutters-and-cnc-machines/ |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Hoskins's own innovations include a superior billiard chalk, materials used to construct race tracks (including the Washington Park Race Tracks in Chicago), safety paper for bank checks, a method for destroying weeds, and a gasoline blowtorch.<ref name=\"CHiC2\" /><ref name=\"magazineclipping\"/>\n\n==Inventions==\n===Electric heating coil===\nWilliam Hoskins is credited with invention of the electric [[Heating element|heating coil]]. In the early 1900s, having worked on a form of [[nichrome]] known as [[chromel]], working with Marsh over the alloy he deduced the usage which could be used as a heating element.<ref name=\"magazineclipping\">{{Cite web |title=The William Hoskins I know |author=Redman, L.V. |work=repository.library.northwestern.edu |date= |access-date=January 2, 2019 |url= http://repository.library.northwestern.edu/fedora/get/inu:inu-mntb-0005391474-pg-7e363cb4-0029-4057-b60e-342a6e4704f0/PDF|publisher=The Chemical Bulletin |language= |quote=}}</ref> The heating coil was created using nichrome, and was later used in early versions of [[Toaster#Development of the heating element|the toaster]], and the [[Kettle#Electric kettles|electric kettle]].<ref name=\"George 2003\">{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SzdrtFSFG6IC&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=%22William+Hoskins%22+high-resistance+wire+electric+heating | title=Antique Electric Waffle Irons 1900\u20131960: A History of the Appliance Industry in 20th Century America | last=George | first=William F. | publisher=Trafford Publishing | year=2003 | page=20 | accessdate=August 16, 2008 | isbn=1-55395-632-X }}</ref> The heating coil was one of the first projects for ''Hoskins Manufacturing Co.''; Hoskins had considered manufacturing toasters, but later abandoned the plans to focus on the coil itself.<ref name=\"esl-_Adva\">{{Cite web |title=Advanced Level: Reading Comprehension - Sentence Gap Fill - History of the Toaster - Answer Sheet {{!}} ESL Lounge |work=ESL Lounge |access-date=January 2, 2019 |url=http://www.esl-lounge.com/level5/level-5-advanced-reading-toasters-sentence-gap-fill-ans.php |quote=AEH's proximity to Hoskins Manufacturing and the fact that the patent was filed only two months after the Marsh patents suggests collaboration and that the device was to use chromel wiring. One of the first applications the Hoskins company had considered for chromel was toasters, but eventually abandoned such efforts to focus on making the wire itself. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831155343/http://www.esl-lounge.com/level5/level-5-advanced-reading-toasters-sentence-gap-fill-ans.php |archive-date=August 31, 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n===Billiard chalk===\n[[Image:Spinks Billiard Chalk box top ca 1900.jpg|thumb|right|Box top of a box of a dozen cubes of William A. Spinks Company billiard chalk, ca. 1900\u20131910. Note the endorsement by champion [[Jacob Schaefer Sr.]]]]\n\nIn the late 19th century,<ref name=\"jdmi_andW\">{{Cite web |title=William Hoskins for cue chalk  |author= |work=Days to Remember |date= |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url= https://jdmitchelldesigns.wordpress.com/tag/and-william-hoskins-for-cue-chalk/ }}</ref> actual [[chalk]] (generally [[calcium]] [[carbonate]], also known as [[calcite]] or carbonate of [[Calcium oxide|lime]]) was often used in [[cue sport]]s on the leather tips of [[cue stick]]s to better grip the [[Billiard ball|cue ball]], but players experimented with other powdery, abrasive substances, since chalk itself was {{em|too}} abrasive, and over time damaged the game equipment.<ref name=\"Tobey1\">Tobey, Eddie (November 9, 2006). \"Billiards Chalk\", ''EZineArticles.com''; retrieved February 24, 2007. Blocked URL: ezinearticles.com/?Billiards-Chalk&id=354398 {{Unreliable source?|date=January 2010|reason=eZineArticle is like AllExperts.com and WP itself, a tertiary source that we can't use.}}</ref><ref name=\"Russell1\">[http://ezinearticles.com/?Billiards---The-Transformation-Years-1845---1897&id=117753 \"Billiards \u2014 The Transformation Years: 1845\u20131897\"], Russell, Michael; ''EZineArticles.com'', December 23, 2005; retrieved 24 February 24, 2007. The article was used as the source for ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'', season 6, episode [http://www.crimelab.nl/transcripts.php?series=1&season=6&episode=22 \"Time of Your Death\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213083800/http://www.crimelab.nl/transcripts.php?series=1&season=6&episode=22 |date=February 13, 2012 }}, in which pool chalk plays a small but crucial role; the show perpetuated the \"axolite\" for \"aloxite\" error in this article.</ref> In 1892,<ref name=\"Russell1\" /> the aforementioned [[Balkline and straight rail|straight rail billiards]] pro William Spinks was particularly impressed by a piece of natural chalk-like substance obtained in [[France]], and presented it to Hoskins for analysis.  Hoskins, having encountered such material before, was able to determine that it was [[Volcanism|volcanic]] ash ([[pumice]]), probably from [[Mount Etna]], [[Sicily]].  The two of them experimented with different formulations to achieve the cue ball \"{{Cuegloss|Action|action}}\" that Spinks sought.<ref name=\"Clark1\" />\n\nThey settled on a mixture of Illinois-sourced<ref name=\"Clark1\" /> [[silica]] with small amounts of [[corundum]] or aloxite<ref name=\"Patent578514\" /> ([[aluminum]] [[oxide]], AL<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>),<ref name=\"Chem1\">[http://www.chemindustry.com/chemicals/14835.html \"Aloxite\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070625100844/http://www.chemindustry.com/chemicals/14835.html |date=June 25, 2007 }}, ''ChemIndustry.com'' database, retrieved February 24, 2007.</ref><ref name=\"PubChem\">[https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?sid=158,243 \"Substance Summary: Aluminum Oxide\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406175207/http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/summary/summary.cgi?sid=158,243 |date=April 6, 2014 }}, ''PubChem Database'', National Library of Medicine, US National Institutes of Health, retrieved February 24, 2007.</ref> founding the William A. Spinks Company in Chicago<ref name=\"Clark1\" /> after securing a patent on March 9, 1897.<ref name=\"Patent578514\" />  Spinks later left the company, but it retained his name and was subsequently run by Hoskins, and later by Hoskins's cousin<ref name=\"Clark1\" /> Edmund F. {{sic|hide=y|Hoskin|reason=His side of the family dropped the -s at the end of the surname.}},<ref name=\"Patent1524132\">{{US patent|1524132}}, January 27, 1925.</ref> after Hoskins moved on to other projects.\n\nThe William A. Spinks Company product (still emulated by modern manufacturers with slightly different, proprietary silicate compounds) effectively revolutionized billiards,<ref name=\"Tobey1\" /><ref name=\"Russell1\" /> by providing a cue tip friction enhancer that allowed the tip to grip the cue ball briefly<ref name=\"Patent578514\" /> and impart a previously unattainable amount of {{sic|hide=y|reason=Not capitalized in this context.|\"{{Cuegloss|english}}\"}} (spin),<ref name=\"Russell1\" /> which consequently allowed more precise and more extreme {{Cuegloss|Position|cue ball control}}, made {{Cuegloss|Miscue|miscuing}} less likely, made {{Cuegloss|Semi-mass\u00e9|swerve}} and {{lang|fr|{{Cuegloss|mass\u00e9}}}} (curve, or even reversing) shots plausible, and eventually spawned the cue sport of [[artistic billiards]] almost a century later.  Even the basic {{Cuegloss|draw}} and {{Cuegloss|follow}} shots of modern billiards games depend heavily on the effects and properties of modern billiard \"chalk\".<ref name=\"bill_Pool\">{{Cite web |title=Pool Pointers: pool\\billiard instruction featuring photos of famous pool players by Billie Billing and Billie Billiard Promotions |work=billiebilliards.com |access-date=December 31, 2018 |url= https://www.billiebilliards.com/pointers006.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131227020451/http://www.billiebilliards.com/pointers006.html |archive-date=December 27, 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n<!--\nONES TO WORK INTO THIS:\n*\"Chairmen of the Chicago Section of ACS\", A Guide to the Chemical History of Chicago. [http://chemhistory-chicago.org/acs.htm]\n*http://www.toaster.org/hoskins.html\n*http://www.toaster.org/hoskins2.html\n*http://www.toaster.org/toastove.html -->\n\n{{Cue sports nav}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoskins, William}}\n[[Category:American carom billiards players]]\n[[Category:American inventors]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Hoskins_(inventor)"}
{"title_page": "Soul (2020 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|Upcoming American computer-animated film}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use list-defined references|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Soul\n| image          = Soul Poster.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| director       = [[Pete Docter]]\n| producer       = [[Dana Murray]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Pete Docter\n* [[Mike Jones (screenwriter)|Mike Jones]]<ref name=\"THR\" />\n* [[Kemp Powers]]\n* [[Tina Fey]]<ref name=\"EWInterview\" />\n}}\n| story          = Pete Docter\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jamie Foxx]]\n* [[Tina Fey]]\n* [[Questlove]]\n* [[Phylicia Rashad]]\n* [[Daveed Diggs]]\n* [[Angela Bassett]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|11|20|United States}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Soul''''' is an upcoming 2020 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[comedy film]] produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]] and [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]] to be distributed by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]]. It is written and directed by [[Pete Docter]], and co-written and co-directed by [[Kemp Powers]]. The film stars the voices of [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Tina Fey]], [[Questlove]], [[Phylicia Rashad]], [[Daveed Diggs]], and [[Angela Bassett]].\n\n''Soul'' is scheduled for release on November 20, 2020.\n\n==Premise==\nJoe Gardner, a middle school music teacher, has long dreamed of performing jazz music onstage, and finally gets a chance after impressing other jazz musicians during an [[opening act]] at the [[Half Note Club]].  However, an untimely accident causes Gardner\u2019s soul to be separated from his body and begin to proceed to ''[[Afterlife|The Great Beyond]]'', Gardner escapes to ''[[Pre-existence|The Great Before]]'', a world where souls develop personalities, quirks, and traits before being sent off to [[Earth]]. There, Gardner must work with souls in training at ''The Great Before'', such as 22, a soul with a dim view on the concept of life, in order to return to Earth before his body dies.<ref name=\"D23\" />\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jamie Foxx]] as Joe Gardner, a passionate music teacher whose soul gets separated from his body after an accident.<ref name=\"D23\" />\n* [[Tina Fey]] as 22, a soul trapped in The Great Before with a dim view of life.<ref name=\"D23\" />\n* [[Questlove]] as Curly, a [[drummer]] in Joe's band.<ref name=\"Polygon\" /><ref name=\"DisInsiderTwitter\" />\n* [[Phylicia Rashad]] as Joe's mother.<ref name=\"Polygon\" /><ref name=\"DisInsiderTwitter\" />\n* [[Daveed Diggs]] as Paul, Joe's neighborhood nemesis.<ref name=\"D23\" /><ref name=\"Polygon\" /><ref name=\"DisInsiderTwitter\" />\n* [[Angela Bassett]] as Dorothea Williams<ref name=\"BassettTwitter\" />\n* [[John Ratzenberger]]<ref name=\"RatzenbergerCast\"/>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn January 2016, it was announced that Pete Docter, head of Pixar, was working on a new film.<ref name=\"DocterAnnounement\" /><ref name=\"MorrisInterview\" /> \n\nIn June 2018, it was announced that Docter was planning to complete his film despite being appointed Chief Creative Officer at [[Pixar]] after [[John Lasseter]]'s departure.<ref name=\"LasseterDeparture\" /> In June 2019, Pixar announced a new film titled ''Soul'' with Docter directing and Dana Murray producing,<ref name=\"DeadlineReport\" /> with a synopsis released on [[Twitter]] about a cosmic journey through New York City.<ref name=\"PixarSoulTwitter\" />\n\nMurray said that the film will \"(take audiences) to a world where no one\u2019s ever been, well, for a long time\", while co writer/co director [[Kemp Powers]] said that it is \"completely different\" to Docter's previous films. Powers also said that the film will answer important questions in \"a really fun way\".<ref name=\"EWInterview\"/> [[Tina Fey]] also contributed to the screenplay, having helped to write her character's lines.<ref name=\"EWInterview\"/>\n\nPixar chose to portray the film's main character as a musician, because they wanted a \"profession the audience could root for\", and settled for a musician after trying for a scientist, which \"[didn't feel] so naturally pure as a musician's life\".<ref name=\"EWInterview\"/> Docter described ''Soul'' as \"an exploration of, where should your focus be? What are the things that, at the end of the day, are really going to be the important things that you look back on and go, 'I spent a worthy amount of my limited time on Earth worrying or focused on that'?\".<ref name=\"EWInterview\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nOn August 24, 2019, [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Tina Fey]], [[Questlove]], [[Phylicia Rashad]] and [[Daveed Diggs]] were announced as starring in the film.<ref name=\"D23\" /><ref name=\"Polygon\" /> ''Soul'' is Pixar's first film to feature an African-American protagonist.<ref name=\"SoulFacts\" /> On March 17, 2020, [[Angela Bassett]] announced she was cast.<ref name=\"BassettTwitter\">{{cite tweet|author=Angela Bassett|user=ImAngelaBassett|number=1231308814399369216|title=Hey Everybody you good? This summer, discover your brilliant, passionate self! So thrilled to finally let the world know that I am part of Disney and Pixar\u2019s new movie Soul! You\u2019ll be hearing a lot more from my character Dorothea Williams very soon. #PixarSoul|date=February 22, 2020|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> On April 13, [[John Ratzenberger]] joined the voice cast.<ref name=\"RatzenbergerCast\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|url=https://collider.com/disney-pixar-soul-raya-and-the-last-dragon-new-release-dates/|title=Disney Moves Pixar\u2019s \u2018Soul\u2019 to Fall, \u2018Raya and the Last Dragon\u2019 to Next Year|website=Collider|date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Animation===\nThe filmmakers animated the souls featured in the film in a \"vaporous\", \"ethereal\", and \"non physical\" way, having based their designs on definitions about souls given to them by various religious and cultural representatives. Docter described it as \"a huge challenge\", as the animators are \"used to toys, cars, things that are much more substantial and easily referenced\", though he felt the animation team \"really put some cool stuff together that's really indicative of those words but also relatable\".<ref name=\"EWInterview\"/>\n\n===Music===\nDuring the 2019 [[D23 Expo]], [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] were revealed to be composing the film's score, while [[Jon Batiste]] will be writing jazz songs for the film.<ref name=\"D23\"/>\n\n==Release==\n''Soul'' was originally scheduled to be released in the United States on June 19, 2020,<ref name=\"DisneyReleaseSchedule\" /> but due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]], it was delayed to November 20, 2020.<ref name=\"ReleasePushBack\" />\n\n===Marketing===\nThe film's teaser trailer was released on November 7, 2019.<ref name=\"TeaserTrailer\"/> The first full trailer was released on March 12, 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/amp/behind-screen/soul-cast-pixar-reveals-names-at-d23-1234134 |title=\u2018Soul\u2019 Cast: Pixar Reveals Names At D23 |last=Glardyna |first=Carolin |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826143500/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/amp/behind-screen/soul-cast-pixar-reveals-names-at-d23-1234134 |archive-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DeadlineReport\">